There have been some problems with enumeration literals in ATL
(see: https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=135699)

I stumbled on closely-related problems with Ecore => Ecore model transformations
involving ATL rules like:

from
 x:MOF!EEnum
to
 y:MOF!EEnum(... eLiterals<-x.eLiterals ...)

The problem is due to the way ATL converts "external" objects
(in this case an Ecore Enumerator/EEnumLiteral object)
into ATL VM objects of a type ASMOclAny.

for Ecore Enumerator, the conversion is: 
(see: org.atl.engine.repositories.emf4atl.ASMEMFModelElement)

ASMOclAny emf2ASM(StackFrame frame, Object value) {
...
 } else if(value instanceof Enumerator) {
    ret = new ASMEnumLiteral(((Enumerator)value).getName());
 } ...

i.e., ASMEnumLiteral is a wrapper around Enumerator.getName(), just a string.
It looses important information that should be preserved:

Enumerator.getLiteral()
Enumerator.getValue()

Without this info, it is impossible to, e.g., 
preserve an enumeration declared in something like this:

enum { answer = 42; }

the best we'd get would be:

enum { answer = 1; }

Worse, because ASMEnumLiteral is "just" a wrapper around a java.lang.String,
it breaks the counterpart conversion from ASM to Ecore:

Object asm2EMF(StackFrame frame, ASMOclAny value, ...) 
...
} else if (value instanceof ASMEnumLiteral) {
  String name = ((ASMEnumLiteral)value).getName();
  EClassifier type =  ((EClass)((ASMEMFModelElement)getMetaobject()).object)
    .getEStructuralFeature(propName).getEType();
  ret = ((EEnum)type).getEEnumLiteral(name).getInstance();
}

The problem here is that when executing something like:

x,y:EEnum
x.eLiterals <- y.eLiterals

the ATL VM must iterate over the EEnum.eLiterals collection of 'y'
for each value (i.e., Ecore Enumerator)
it does:
1) Enumerator => emf2ASM() => ASMEnumLiteral
2) ASMEnumLiteral => asm2EMF() => ???

In this case, the above logic fails because we're in a context
where there is not enough "meta" object context to find what EEnum
type the result of (2) should be added to.

This means that simple rules like this:

rule enumLiteral {
 from
  x : MOF!EEnumLiteral
 to
  y : MOF!EEnumLiteral(
   name <- x.getName(),
   value <- x.getValue(),
   literal <- x.getLiteral()
  )
}

rule enums {
 from
  e : MOF!EEnum
 to
  f : MOF!EEnum (
   name <- e.name,
   eLiterals <- e.eLiterals
  )
}

This doesn't work! 

The asm2EMF convertion trips ClassCastException errors
because the "type" is EEnumLiteral, not EEnum.

To fix this problem, there is a small patch necessary
to use to "preserve" the Enumerator.{value,literal} information
after conversion by emf2ASM into an ASMEnumLiteral object.

Once this is done, the conversion back from ASMEnumLiteral to EEnumLiteral
must be done "implicitly" by operating on OCL collections of literals; i.e:

rule makeEnumLiteral(l : MOF!EEnumLiteral) {
 to
  enl : MOF!EEnumLiteral (
   name <- l.getName(),
   value <- l.getValue()
  )
 do {
  enl; -- we need the "result" of this rule!
 }
}

rule enums {
 from
  e : MOF!EEnum
 to
  f : MOF!EEnum (
   name <- e.name,
   eLiterals <- e.eLiterals->collect(elit | thisModule.makeEnumLiteral(elit))
  )
}

This works!

Why? Take the small patch, rebuilt ATL and try it.

The long answer is that the "collect(...)" expression is "compiled"
into a bunch of ATL VM code that, essentially, does some magic
that can be "procedurally" described like this:

Sequence(ASMEnumLiterals) temp = Sequence{};
foreach eCoreEnumLiteral in e.eLiterals {
  let enl : ASMEnumLiteral = "call"(makeEnumLiteral(emf2ASM(eCoreEnumLiteral)));
  temp = temp "include" enl;
}
f.eLiterals = asm2EMF(temp);

the conversion of an ASM collection converts each element;
but it happens in a "frame" where "f" turns out to have type=EEnum !

I'm not sure if my explanation is 100% correct but after 2 days
of beating my head on this nasty bug, this seems to be a reasonable
explanation for bug reporting purposes.

With the above patch, it is possible to generate EMF annotations
from ATL transformations. 

module ...
create OUT : MOF from ...

rule makeAnnotation (sourceURI : String) {
  to
    ann : MOF!EAnnotation( source <- sourceURI )
  do {
    ann; -- get the result
  }
}

rule OperationInvariant {
  from 
    ... -- some source element/condition triggering this rule
  using {
    genmodelDirectives : MOF!EAnnotation =
      thisModule.makeAnnotation('http://www.eclipse.org/OCL/examples/ocl');
    details : Map(String, String) = 
      Map{ ('invariant',
            'not manager.oclIsUndefined() implies employees->notEmpty()')
         }; -- I'm using Christian's example to illustrate how to do it in ATL
  }
  to
    oo : MOF!EOperation (...)
  do {
    ...
    genmodelDirectives.details <- details;
    oo.eAnnotations <-
    if details.isEmpty()
    then Sequence{} -- don't pollute the EMF model w/ empty annotations
    else Sequence{ genmodelDirectives } -- produce annotations only when needed
    endif;
  }
}

The transformation can be simplified a bit by replacing
the 'if details.isEmpty() ... endif' test above with
the equivalent line below:

oo.eAnnotations <- Sequence{ genmodelDirectives }

However, there's a tradeoff between transformation complexity
vs. keeping the EMF models free of incidental junk.
If avoiding junk matters, then the test above will only
produce <eAnnotations ...> tags in the EMF model
only when there is at least one 'detail' entry.

To avoid generating 'junk' annotations (i.e., no details) in ATL,
we have to do something slightly trickier than I described earlier:

rule makeAnnotation (sourceURI : String, annotationDetails : Map(String,String)) {
  to
    ann : MOF!EAnnotation( source <- sourceURI, details <- annotationDetails )
  do {
    ann; -- get the result
  }
}

rule OperationInvariant {
  from 
    ... -- some source element/condition triggering this rule
  using {
    details : Map(String, String) = 
      Map{ ('invariant',
            'not manager.oclIsUndefined() implies employees->notEmpty()')
         }; -- I'm using Christian's example to illustrate how to do it in ATL
  }
  to
    oo : MOF!EOperation (...)
  do {
    ...
    oo.eAnnotations <-
    if details.isEmpty()
    then Sequence{} -- don't pollute the EMF model w/ empty annotations
    else 
      let genmodelDirectives : MOF!EAnnotation =
        thisModule.makeAnnotation
        ('http://www.eclipse.org/OCL/examples/ocl', details)
      in Sequence{ genmodelDirectives }
    endif;
  }
}

In other words, we have to defer the creation of MOF!EAnnotation nodes
until we know for sure that they are needed -- i.e., details.isNotEmpty().

