More information:
Proposed fix for IntegerTypeImpl.java (and an analogous modification to RealTypeImpl.java):

 new OperationImpl(this, "==", getTypeSystem().getBooleanType(), new Type[] { getTypeSystem()
                        .getObjectType() }) {
                    @Override
                    public Object evaluateInternal(final Object target, final Object[] params) {
                        if (target == null)
                            return new Boolean(target == params[0]);
                        if (params[0] == null) return false; // <- INSERTED
                        return new Boolean(toLong(target).equals(toLong(params[0])));
                    }

                },
 new OperationImpl(this, "!=", getTypeSystem().getBooleanType(), new Type[] { getTypeSystem()
                        .getObjectType() }) {
                    @Override
                    public Object evaluateInternal(final Object target, final Object[] params) {
                        if (target == null)
                            return new Boolean(target != params[0]);
                        if (params[0] == null) return true; // <- INSERTED
                        return new Boolean(!toLong(target).equals(toLong(params[0])));
                    }
                },

Often, constraints depend on each other. That means, if some constraint A does not validate, there's no reason to evaluate another constraint. Currently, this cannot be expressed, resulting in all kinds of follow-up errors or exceptions. This could be solved by supporting dependencies between constraints:
Here is a context with a new construct, a constraint ID, which can be added optionally before the constraint itself.
aConstraindID: context SomeType ERROR "message": expression;
Here's the constraint that depends on the above one:
context SomeType ERROR "anotherMessage" depends aConstraintID: expression;
This constraint will only be checked if the constraint identified by the ID mentioned after "depends" has been validated successfully.

